She turned to a blank page and noted the date. Below it she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648".
"Do old memories freshen up?" Ivory asked and looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never let Kari out, considering her a "blemish." She was born deaf and was the only daughter of the family, her siblings were all boys.
Something similar happened to Ivory as well. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as though the world was changing. As punishment for this nonconformity, Ivory was given tasks where they spent most of the time alone.
In addition, Ivory was also forced to serve the princess. However, it did not make a big difference to Ivory, as Ivory had also gained a friend.
"You're going to have a birthday soon, aren't you?", Ivory asked, as she thought that the princess was going to have a birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sad flicker in her light blue eyes.
"Would you like to celebrate your birthday?", Ivory asked and thought about the last time the princess had answered this question.
"No", Kari knocked. Ivory knew that this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother was banished. Ivory had been a baby at that time, but she remembered how upset the servants and the town's residents had been. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a popular queen. And that she strangely could also predict things that then actually came true.
"Well, what do you want to do?", Ivory asked. Kari looked at Ivory excitedly. She was holding a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
White, various blue shades.
Brushes in six different sizes.
Easel
"Are you going to let me take care of these things for you?", Ivory asked the quiet princess, whose braids swung back and forth with her intense knocking. "Yes?" Ivory chuckled quietly. The otherwise closed-off princess showed so much enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
"Okay! Will we see each other later?", Ivory asked, stood up and navigated through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes and snuggled up in her bed blanket.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her reach, such as paints.
Ivory walked down the corridors again, trying to ignore the whispers of the maids.
"I've heard that she is supposed to be possessed by Queen Eirwen and that's why she keeps going back into this room."
"I heard that she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, that's not normal, is it?"
Ivory covered her ears because she simply couldn't ignore the gossip, and she continued on. The room of the royal painter was located in the eastern wing behind the second door on the left side.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as beautifully decorated as Karis' door. On it stood the White Dragon, one of the six primordial dragons which, allegedly, Frostfell was supposed to have created. For a history-obsessed painter, the White Dragon on the door certainly made sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual chaos. Color splatters everywhere, brushes and paper scattered all over the room, easels that covered every inch of the wall. Unexpectedly, however, a different sight presented itself. The entire room was clean, and in front of a red velvet background stood a single chair. On the chair sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being portrayed at that moment.
"Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch as your future king is portrayed?" Aquilo asked and winked at Ivory.
"Sorry, little prince," Ivory said, largely ignored him and started gathering the things the quiet princess wanted. "I'm just here to pick up some art things."
"My little girl wants to go already?", asked Aquilo. "I want you to stay, though."
"I'm not, however." Ivory found the art supplies on the list and put them in a box. "Also, I'm not a girl."
The prince, however, had a different opinion. "Ach sweetie, that's just a phase! As you grow older, you'll grow out of that!" he said unclearly.
"I have to go," Ivory said and felt uneasy by the prince's answer. As Ivory stood there, all the ugly comments he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past came flooding back to him. I just want to get out of here.
"Are you going already?" Suddenly the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud objections of the royal painter.
"That's no behavior for a future king!" said Ivory.
"No one will find out. People won't believe you and the painter will keep quiet if his life is worth anything to him." He looked at the painter briefly and then leaned in closer to Ivory. "What do you think about a date?"
"Do you actually know what the word 'no' means?", Ivory said and pushed the Crown Prince away.
"No," Aquilo replied with a smile. Of course, the Crown Prince, who can have anything he wants, doesn't know what the word "no" means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why on earth would you want to go out with someone like me? You must have at least 100 admirers."
"Actually, it's 50," he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He tossed his hair back, which whirled around in the cold air.
"Now understand it! Why me? I'm a danger to the palace."
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced Ivory to look at him.
